 both in the select committee context but also doing his own research   he has come up with a tenpoint plan for the industry  a series of practical proposals some short term some mid to longterm   we thought his plan worthy of circulation email any comments to malcolmrishisunakcom   ten steps to help save british dairying   last week i spoke to an yearold farmer in my constituency who told me that in a lifetime of dairy farming he had never seen times as so bad with farm gate milk prices falling  per cent in a year  in many cases below the cost of production  its far from an exaggeration   i have spent the last few weeks speaking to dairy farmers industry experts and government ministers about the terrible difficulties the industry is facing its clear nobody can wave a magic wand and resolve a situation ultimately caused by a global glut of milk but i believe there are ten key steps that can and must be taken if we are to protect this most valuable element of our rural community    more retailers giving farmers a fair deal many supermarkets have worked hard through a time of rockbottom global milk prices to ensure that british farmers receive a sustainable price that said more can be done and it is absolutely vital every major retailer pays a fair price for british dairy produce you can see how your supermarket treats its famers by checking the national farmers union website  if youre not happy vote with your wallet    an end to milk being used a permanent loss leader all of us have seen the price of milk plummet in recent years with many supermarkets now charging only ł for four pints this kind of pricing can have widely detrimental effects thats because low prices in supermarkets force down prices all across the market forcing your corner shop to cut its milk price in order to compete in turn putting pressure on milk producers milk is a quality product and pricing should reflect that    better labelling of british produce it might seem like there is little that could be more english than a slice of cheddar but what many consumers dont know is that many of the major cheddar brands on the shelves are produced in europe we need to have clearer packaging that empowers consumers to buy british     more domestic production of dairy products its a scandal that two thirds of our cheese and  per cent of our butter is imported from overseas we need to invest more in processing technology to make sure we are adding value to british milk by turning more of it into british butter yogurt and cheese rather than importing so much    more supply chain transparency and enforcement we know how much a farmer gets paid for a pint of milk and we know how much we pay for it in the shops what we dont know is how big the margins are inbetween we need to work towards the kind of transparency that allows us to follow milk from farmer to shelf in order to ensure a fair price is being paid at every stage good supply chain practices then need to be enforced by a tough grocery code adjudicator and strong code of practice    more dairy producer organisations groups of farmers banding together to negotiate a better sale price for milk and a lower purchase price for feed and machinery are commonplace across europe particularly in the successful german market in the uk we currently have only one such producer organisation if farmers are going to balance out the power of big processors and retailers that needs to change    government must buy british national government is working hard to purchase british dairy products but more can be done at a regional level we must push local government hospitals schools and military establishments to do more     a working dairy futures market futures are a way for farmers to agree a prearranged price for milk they will produce in the future the price stability this can give has the potential to be invaluable to the volatile dairy industry we need the uk to follow in the footsteps of the usa and new zealand in making a working dairy futures market available    review of levy board spending every dairy farmer in the uk currently pays a percentage of their income to a government run levy board many farmers feel that more of that money needs to be spent promoting the benefits of milk and encouraging consumers to choose british it is vital that farmers feel like their levy money is being spent in a way that actually helps them    immediate financial assistance the eu has announced a m crisis fund to support vulnerable dairy farmers and we must get our fair share also it is important that regular cap payments to farmers should be made as quickly as possible to ease cash flow problems lastly hmrc and banks must understand the inherent volatility in farming incomes and be flexible in how they treat farmers    comment from rishi    nd october  without its dairy farmers yorkshires magical landscape would soon see its lush fields turn to scrub and its drystonewalls go unrepaired meanwhile with britain already only  per cent selfsufficient in food our countrys ability to feed itself in a time of crisis would be diminished only by working together can we preserve our dairy industry and with it our beautiful countryside for generations to come   spotted on a london underground billboard   nd october      as was stated by the eagleeyed reader its not exactly a positive image of our industry   ppl arla amba milk price increase netts down to ppl   th september  from th september the arla amba member milk price will increase by ppl  euro centslitre however the strength of sterling means the currency smoothing mechanism eliminates ppl resulting in a nett ppl gain   this results in the following wwwmilkpricescom standard litre prices   arla amco members                        ppl arla amco tesco suppliers   ppl   first milk haverfordwest producers to receive an extra  to ppl courtesy of tesco   th september  the  or so first milk members who supply the coops haverfordwest creamery have b